WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:25.330
&gt;&gt; Eugene Flanagan: Hello,
my name is Eugene Flanagan.

00:00:25.330 --> 00:00:28.950 position:56%
I'm the director of National
Programs at the Library of Congress.

00:00:28.950 --> 00:00:30.480
And it's my great pleasure
to welcome you

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:33.040
to this morning's master
class, the kickoff event

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:35.460
of our daylong symposium.

00:00:35.460 --> 00:00:37.620
The symposium is sponsored
by the library's Poetry

00:00:37.620 --> 00:00:40.920
and Literature Center, as well as
the Folger Shakespeare Library,

00:00:40.920 --> 00:00:43.970
the PEN Faulkner Foundation,
and the [inaudible] Foundation.

00:00:43.970 --> 00:00:48.270
I want to thank them, and I want
to thank We Need Diverse Books,

00:00:48.270 --> 00:00:50.240
the grassroots organization
responsible

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:54.250
for coordinating today's master
class, and whose goal is,

00:00:54.250 --> 00:00:57.640
and I quote, to produce and
promote literature that reflects

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:00.040
and honors the lives
of all young people,

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:01.540
and in doing so to create a world

00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:03.780
in which all children
can see themselves

00:01:03.780 --> 00:01:05.320
as in the pages of a book.

00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:09.910
The symposium, and this morning's
master class in particular,

00:01:09.910 --> 00:01:12.880
started with one writer,
Kwame Alexander.

00:01:12.880 --> 00:01:15.640
I would like to thank Kwame
for his work with the Poetry

00:01:15.640 --> 00:01:19.460
and Literature Center, and for
applying a full court press

00:01:19.460 --> 00:01:21.380
to create the terrific
programming that we

00:01:21.380 --> 00:01:24.010
and the Folger Shakespeare
Library are presenting today.

00:01:24.010 --> 00:01:28.950
And thank you for appreciating
that one.

00:01:28.950 --> 00:01:32.890
Kwame is a poet, educator,
and author of 21 books.

00:01:32.890 --> 00:01:37.020
He has written books for children
of all ages, including Surfs Up,

00:01:37.020 --> 00:01:40.490
a picture book [inaudible]
middle grade novel,

00:01:40.490 --> 00:01:44.050
and He Said She Said,
a young adult novel.

00:01:44.050 --> 00:01:48.210
His book, The Crossover, received
the 2015 John Newbery Medal

00:01:48.210 --> 00:01:51.270
for the most distinguished
contribution to American literature

00:01:51.270 --> 00:01:55.810
for children, and the Lee Bennett
Hopkins Poetry Award presented

00:01:55.810 --> 00:01:58.340
annually to an American
poet or anthologist

00:01:58.340 --> 00:02:02.870
for the most outstanding new
book of children's poetry.

00:02:02.870 --> 00:02:05.340
Kwame also works with students

00:02:05.340 --> 00:02:07.440
in the classroom through
Books in a Day.

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:10.170
His program teaches and
empowers teenagers to write

00:02:10.170 --> 00:02:12.250
and publish their own books.

00:02:12.250 --> 00:02:16.620 position:56%
And he is founder of Leap for Ghana,
an international literacy project

00:02:16.620 --> 00:02:19.150
that builds libraries,
trains teachers,

00:02:19.150 --> 00:02:22.040
and empowers children
through literature.

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:27.680
He has said, again I quote, writing
is active, writing is action,

00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:31.580
writing is activism, writing
is being part of the world,

00:02:31.580 --> 00:02:33.510
and that's what I like to do.

00:02:33.510 --> 00:02:37.530
As he gets us started here today,
please join me in welcoming a man

00:02:37.530 --> 00:02:41.510
of words and actions,
Kwame Alexander.

00:02:41.510 --> 00:02:51.850
[ Applause ]

00:02:51.850 --> 00:02:53.150
&gt;&gt; Kwame Alexander:
Wow, I said all that?

00:02:53.150 --> 00:02:57.430
Thank you, Eugene.

00:02:57.430 --> 00:03:02.760
Thank you to the Library of
Congress, to the Center for Poetry

00:03:02.760 --> 00:03:05.550
and Literature, to the
Center of the Book.

00:03:05.550 --> 00:03:08.610
Thank you to Robert
[assumed spelling]

00:03:08.610 --> 00:03:12.070
and Anya [assumed spelling]
for being excited

00:03:12.070 --> 00:03:15.330
and open to this opportunity.

00:03:15.330 --> 00:03:20.800
Almost a year, if not more,
maybe eight or nine months ago,

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:22.550
and here's how it happened.

00:03:22.550 --> 00:03:26.800
I was on the phone with a friend
of mine named Jacqueline Woodson.

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:31.850
And we text maybe once a week to
find out if we're in the same city,

00:03:31.850 --> 00:03:35.940
because that's really the only
time we get to see each other.

00:03:35.940 --> 00:03:37.240
Are you Minneapolis?

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:38.990
No, I'm in -- I'm in Milwaukee.

00:03:38.990 --> 00:03:41.690
You know, we're close
but we're not there.

00:03:41.690 --> 00:03:44.910
And I said, I was talking to
my editor at Houghton Mifflin,

00:03:44.910 --> 00:03:48.440
which is the publisher of
The Crossover, and I said,

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:52.770
Margaret [assumed spelling], do
you all have any black editors?

00:03:52.770 --> 00:03:54.270
Do you all have any
editors of color?

00:03:54.270 --> 00:03:56.060
You should really think
about hiring somebody.

00:03:56.060 --> 00:03:58.210
And this happened because I --

00:03:58.210 --> 00:04:01.400 position:56%
well, it happened because I had been
thinking about it, but I was sort

00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:05.660
of moved to contact her immediately
because I received an e-mail

00:04:05.660 --> 00:04:06.960
from Jason Low [assumed spelling].

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:08.680
And Jason said, Kwame,
we're doing a survey.

00:04:08.680 --> 00:04:11.040
Can we get your publisher involved?

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:14.760
And I was like, oh, I don't know
if they're going to move on that,

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:18.090 position:56%
but maybe there's another way I can
go about this so let me call and see

00:04:18.090 --> 00:04:21.970
if I can, you know, sort of probe
them to hire some black editors.

00:04:21.970 --> 00:04:24.630
I had a little bit
of cache at this time

00:04:24.630 --> 00:04:28.750
because I had just read an
article in Publishers Weekly

00:04:28.750 --> 00:04:30.170
that said Houghton Mifflin,

00:04:30.170 --> 00:04:35.200
their fourth quarter results were
significantly higher than last year

00:04:35.200 --> 00:04:38.780
because of three things,
some cookbook,

00:04:38.780 --> 00:04:42.320
some educational unit they
had purchased from Scholastic,

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:44.840
and the sales of The Crossover.

00:04:44.840 --> 00:04:48.230
So I said, let me try to use a
little bit of leverage [laughter].

00:04:48.230 --> 00:04:51.190
And my editor's response
was, Kwame, we've tried.

00:04:51.190 --> 00:04:53.230
We've looked for editors of color,

00:04:53.230 --> 00:04:55.590
and there just aren't
a whole lot out there.

00:04:55.590 --> 00:04:57.420
Now two things.

00:04:57.420 --> 00:04:59.010
One, that's a cop out.

00:04:59.010 --> 00:05:00.310
We all know that.

00:05:00.310 --> 00:05:03.990
And number two, well if it's a
cop out where are the editors?

00:05:03.990 --> 00:05:05.290
Where are the writers?

00:05:05.290 --> 00:05:06.590
Where are the marketers?

00:05:06.590 --> 00:05:09.190
Where are the people
of color who need

00:05:09.190 --> 00:05:11.120
to be children's book publishing?

00:05:11.120 --> 00:05:12.530
And so I texted Jackie
[assumed spelling] and said,

00:05:12.530 --> 00:05:13.960
Jackie, let's do a master class.

00:05:13.960 --> 00:05:17.640
I'm going to propose this
to the Library of Congress

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:22.960
and let's get editors,
writers, publishers, marketers,

00:05:22.960 --> 00:05:27.910
promoters of the future
of color in a room

00:05:27.910 --> 00:05:30.670
and let's just share
what we have to say.

00:05:30.670 --> 00:05:34.150
To share what we've been through.

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:37.800
And Robert and Anya were on board.

00:05:37.800 --> 00:05:41.530
And I called up friends
of mine in the industry,

00:05:41.530 --> 00:05:46.370
Cassandra [assumed spelling]
from Scholastic, Jenny Brown now

00:05:46.370 --> 00:05:49.400
at Random House, [inaudible],
Jason from Lee

00:05:49.400 --> 00:05:52.940
and Low, and everybody said yes.

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:55.430
And so that's how we ended
up here in this room.

00:05:55.430 --> 00:05:58.870
It started with an e-mail
from Jason, a text to Jackie,

00:05:58.870 --> 00:06:04.660 position:56%
and it really speaks to how things
work in this industry in particular,

00:06:04.660 --> 00:06:07.290
and just in American in general.

00:06:07.290 --> 00:06:09.510
You can't know what you don't know.

00:06:09.510 --> 00:06:13.030
And the way you find out things
is by people who are interested

00:06:13.030 --> 00:06:17.050
and concerned and care enough to
be able to share things with you,

00:06:17.050 --> 00:06:22.630
resources, opportunities, tools,
tips, tricks, and techniques.

00:06:22.630 --> 00:06:26.490
And I think that's
why we're here today.

00:06:26.490 --> 00:06:28.020
Would you agree?

00:06:28.020 --> 00:06:29.320
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:34.640 position:56%
&gt;&gt; So by a show of hands, people who
want to write or who are writing?

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:35.940
Excellent.

00:06:35.940 --> 00:06:39.140
People who want to be involved
are involved in the business

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:41.300
of literature and publishing?

00:06:41.300 --> 00:06:45.970 position:56%
Lovely, lovely, that's so important.

00:06:45.970 --> 00:06:48.730
Librarians, teachers?

00:06:48.730 --> 00:06:50.070
Excellent.

00:06:50.070 --> 00:06:52.800
And so we're all here
together under one roof.

00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:56.250
I think the end goal -- the
end goal of today is for us

00:06:56.250 --> 00:07:01.620
to certainly be inspired, but
more importantly it's for us

00:07:01.620 --> 00:07:05.150
to leave here with some
practical sort of guidance,

00:07:05.150 --> 00:07:09.950
some rules as they were, that
are going to propel us forward.

00:07:09.950 --> 00:07:16.380 position:56%
So we've got 55 people in this room,
there's no reason why five five, 10,

00:07:16.380 --> 00:07:22.280 position:56%
or 15 of you all when you leave here
today are actively pursuing your

00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:26.620
dream, your idea of what it means
for you to be a part of the world

00:07:26.620 --> 00:07:28.530
of Children's Book Publishing.

00:07:28.530 --> 00:07:29.960
And it is a beautiful world.

00:07:29.960 --> 00:07:33.340 position:56%
And here's the cool part about
children's literature and publishing

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:38.350
when it compares to other
aspects of the publishing world.

00:07:38.350 --> 00:07:40.710
There is no competition.

00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:43.990
Well, no, let me not
say that [laughter].

00:07:43.990 --> 00:07:46.370
Let me not say it like that.

00:07:46.370 --> 00:07:52.230
There is no competitive
energy amongst us.

00:07:52.230 --> 00:07:56.180
When you're in the room where it
happens we all trying to support

00:07:56.180 --> 00:07:57.890
and encourage each other.

00:07:57.890 --> 00:08:00.540
I wish I had gotten into
children's books a long time ago.

00:08:00.540 --> 00:08:03.230
There is a spirit of love.

00:08:03.230 --> 00:08:04.700
There is cooperation.

00:08:04.700 --> 00:08:07.750
Yeah, it's competitive, everybody
wants to sort of do their thing

00:08:07.750 --> 00:08:10.800
and be successful, but we
all support each other,

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:12.860
and you can't ask for
a better industry

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:15.770
if you're a part of
writing to be in.

00:08:15.770 --> 00:08:19.570
I tell poets all the
time in particular,

00:08:19.570 --> 00:08:22.720
if you want to make some money
get into children's books.

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:28.030
We spend a lot of time writing --
you know, as poets we spend a lot

00:08:28.030 --> 00:08:31.180
of time writing and submitting and
trying to get out poems published.

00:08:31.180 --> 00:08:33.230
And it's wonderful.

00:08:33.230 --> 00:08:34.670
And we do it not to make money.

00:08:34.670 --> 00:08:36.200
What, Robert Frost
said there's no poetry

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:37.580
in money and no money in poetry.

00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:39.350
We don't do it to make money.

00:08:39.350 --> 00:08:41.230
We do it because we love to do it.

00:08:41.230 --> 00:08:44.100 position:56%
But at some point you have a family.

00:08:44.100 --> 00:08:45.990
I have two kids and I have a wife.

00:08:45.990 --> 00:08:49.400
And you have to figure out
how to sort of, you know,

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:52.390
marry the art and the commerce.

00:08:52.390 --> 00:08:53.880
And so how do you do that?

00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:59.550
I posit that if you're a poet
you write a wonderful book of 40

00:08:59.550 --> 00:09:06.420
or 50 poems and it's -- you know,
you sell three or 4000 copies.

00:09:06.420 --> 00:09:12.960 position:56%
And it's okay, it's cool and you
get critical acclaim and you love it

00:09:12.960 --> 00:09:16.980
and you share and you do
your readings and so forth

00:09:16.980 --> 00:09:24.520 position:56%
versus you write one poem and it's a
picture book and maybe you sell five

00:09:24.520 --> 00:09:27.080
or 10,000 copies of
this picture book.

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:28.730
And it's one poem.

00:09:28.730 --> 00:09:30.340
See people, we're going
to get real today.

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:31.810
We're going to talk
[laughter] -- I'm not --

00:09:31.810 --> 00:09:33.760
