00:37:52.200 --> 00:37:56.310 position:56%
And so that, we released it at the
beginning of this year and it was --

00:37:56.310 --> 00:37:58.730
and it's called the
Diversity Baseline Survey.

00:37:58.730 --> 00:38:04.220
And so what that is, is it's
essentially it was taking a look

00:38:04.220 --> 00:38:07.550
at staffing at publishing
and reviewers, right,

00:38:07.550 --> 00:38:10.560
and what the diversity looked
like behind the scenes.

00:38:10.560 --> 00:38:16.610
Now mostly up until this point most
of the feeling about the diversity

00:38:16.610 --> 00:38:19.170
in publishing behind the
scenes was anecdotal.

00:38:19.170 --> 00:38:21.360
You know, people knew
we had a problem

00:38:21.360 --> 00:38:23.880
but they didn't really
know how bad it was,

00:38:23.880 --> 00:38:26.220
and there was certainly
no data to really look at.

00:38:26.220 --> 00:38:29.310
So when we launched
this we wanted to sort

00:38:29.310 --> 00:38:33.980
of establish a baseline number that
essentially would act as something

00:38:33.980 --> 00:38:36.440
that we would be able to
measure progress against,

00:38:36.440 --> 00:38:39.860
whether it's getting better,
staying the same, or getting worse.

00:38:39.860 --> 00:38:44.360
So from an industry overall
you could see that, you know,

00:38:44.360 --> 00:38:52.260
79% of publishing staff is white,
78% is women, 88% is straight,

00:38:52.260 --> 00:38:55.560
and 92% is nondisabled, right.

00:38:55.560 --> 00:39:00.320
And so all in all, you know,
when all was said and done we had

00:39:00.320 --> 00:39:05.860
about 34 publishers participate
and eight major reviewers.

00:39:05.860 --> 00:39:08.470
Three out of the five
big publishers --

00:39:08.470 --> 00:39:11.330
big five publishers
participated in the survey.

00:39:11.330 --> 00:39:14.210
And we were really trying to make
sure that there was a nice mix

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:16.740
of small, medium, and
large publishers.

00:39:16.740 --> 00:39:22.460
You know, when you -- when we could
sort of have a very even, you know,

00:39:22.460 --> 00:39:23.960
viewpoint of what to look at.

00:39:23.960 --> 00:39:30.780
So in the editorial department
there's 82% white, 84% female,

00:39:30.780 --> 00:39:34.490
86% straight, and 92% nondisabled.

00:39:34.490 --> 00:39:38.760
So the interesting part of the
survey I felt was when we began

00:39:38.760 --> 00:39:40.920
to look at departments, right.

00:39:40.920 --> 00:39:45.260
And we looked at the
executive level jobs.

00:39:45.260 --> 00:39:47.010
We looked at the editorial
department.

00:39:47.010 --> 00:39:48.310
We looked at sales.

00:39:48.310 --> 00:39:51.460
We looked at marketing, and we
looked at book reviewers, right.

00:39:51.460 --> 00:39:55.500
And the reason that we singled
out these particular departments,

00:39:55.500 --> 00:39:58.420
because we consider these
departments, you know, gatekeepers.

00:39:58.420 --> 00:40:01.230
These are essentially
the departments

00:40:01.230 --> 00:40:04.640
that have the responsibility
to not only shape, you know,

00:40:04.640 --> 00:40:08.760 position:56%
what the books are, the main product
that we sell, but also the people

00:40:08.760 --> 00:40:11.940
who sell them, the people who
market them, and book reviewers

00:40:11.940 --> 00:40:13.300
who are basically the taste makers.

00:40:13.300 --> 00:40:16.960
They're telling you what to
read and what not to read.

00:40:16.960 --> 00:40:20.540
And so you can see that the
diversity is a little less

00:40:20.540 --> 00:40:25.840
so at book reviewers and 89%
are white, 87% are women,

00:40:25.840 --> 00:40:29.790
91% straight, and 88% nondisabled.

00:40:29.790 --> 00:40:39.050
So when we sent the survey out,
1524 reviewers were surveyed,

00:40:39.050 --> 00:40:44.050
11,713 publishing employees
were survey,

00:40:44.050 --> 00:40:48.940
which comes out to a
total 13,237 surveys.

00:40:48.940 --> 00:40:52.790
The response rate was about 26%.

00:40:52.790 --> 00:40:59.210
So I think what may be at work
here is a phenomenon known

00:40:59.210 --> 00:41:00.910
as cultural fit.

00:41:00.910 --> 00:41:06.010
Cultural fit is defined as the
tendency, conscious, or unconscious

00:41:06.010 --> 00:41:09.540
for executives, editors,
marketers, salespeople,

00:41:09.540 --> 00:41:12.920
reviewers that work with,
develop, and recommend books by

00:41:12.920 --> 00:41:15.620 position:56%
and about people who look like them.

00:41:15.620 --> 00:41:19.920
And I think cultural fit
relates to corporate culture.

00:41:19.920 --> 00:41:24.150
And it definitely has something
to do with hiring, okay.

00:41:24.150 --> 00:41:28.910
So, you know, just to illustrate,
you know, how this relates to Lee

00:41:28.910 --> 00:41:31.830
