01:33:11.520 --> 01:33:15.010
I wanted to explore literature and
the history of the written word

01:33:15.010 --> 01:33:17.370
in a way I hadn't previously.

01:33:17.370 --> 01:33:19.550
So I switched to an English major

01:33:19.550 --> 01:33:23.080
and dropped the creative writing
minor, because I also realized

01:33:23.080 --> 01:33:25.280
that I liked writing a
lot more when I did it

01:33:25.280 --> 01:33:27.910
on my own time and in my own time.

01:33:27.910 --> 01:33:32.880
At Spelman I read books by writers
I had never been exposed to before

01:33:32.880 --> 01:33:36.730 position:56%
because I was rarely assigned books
by writers of color in grade school.

01:33:36.730 --> 01:33:41.260
Alice Walker, Gwendolyn Brooks,
James Baldwin, Julia Alvarez,

01:33:41.260 --> 01:33:44.390
Octavia Butler, [inaudible],
the list goes on.

01:33:44.390 --> 01:33:48.750
This was a whole new
kind of education.

01:33:48.750 --> 01:33:52.330
My mind was thoroughly
blown and I was in heaven.

01:33:52.330 --> 01:33:55.670
Spelman is where I read
Persepolis by Marjane Satrapi

01:33:55.670 --> 01:33:58.490
for the first time, a
book that changed my life

01:33:58.490 --> 01:34:01.340
and would form my career later on.

01:34:01.340 --> 01:34:05.040
As I neared the end of my
sophomore year I still was not sure

01:34:05.040 --> 01:34:08.300
of what I would actually
do with an English degree.

01:34:08.300 --> 01:34:13.010
I often ask myself, what do
people do with English degrees?

01:34:13.010 --> 01:34:15.890
Yes, reading books,
writing papers about books,

01:34:15.890 --> 01:34:19.660 position:56%
and talking about books is all quite
lovely, but I knew I couldn't live

01:34:19.660 --> 01:34:24.680
in my little literary non-revenue
generating world forever.

01:34:24.680 --> 01:34:26.390
People would often
ask me if I planned

01:34:26.390 --> 01:34:29.910 position:56%
to be a teacher or go to law school.

01:34:29.910 --> 01:34:33.310
My answer was always
no, no, thank you.

01:34:33.310 --> 01:34:37.090
With this complete lack of
clarity on my own life I started

01:34:37.090 --> 01:34:39.430
to look for a summer job.

01:34:39.430 --> 01:34:42.550
I very much wanted to
do something meaningful,

01:34:42.550 --> 01:34:45.110
something that would
actually mean something to me,

01:34:45.110 --> 01:34:48.620
and do all the studying I
had done so far it justice.

01:34:48.620 --> 01:34:52.350
I did not just want to go back to
halfheartedly selling Cutco knives

01:34:52.350 --> 01:34:57.050 position:56%
out of my parents' house in Delaware
like I had the summer before.

01:34:57.050 --> 01:35:00.340
Spelman has an office of career
planning and development.

01:35:00.340 --> 01:35:04.800
And one day I spent hours there,
browsing their entire catalog

01:35:04.800 --> 01:35:07.690
of internship brochures
and applications.

01:35:07.690 --> 01:35:12.540 position:56%
I looked at every single piece of
paper in every single filing cabinet

01:35:12.540 --> 01:35:14.780
and found a few things
that I thought I could do,

01:35:14.780 --> 01:35:18.680
but nothing that sounded like it
would ignite a fire inside of me.

01:35:18.680 --> 01:35:19.980
Kind of dramatic, right?

01:35:19.980 --> 01:35:22.850
I was quite a vocational
romantic at 19.

01:35:22.850 --> 01:35:27.570
I was feeling kind of bummed and
uninspired when I spotted a pile

01:35:27.570 --> 01:35:30.730
of miscellaneous envelopes
on a small table.

01:35:30.730 --> 01:35:33.890
Among them a familiar
red logo peaked out.

01:35:33.890 --> 01:35:39.420
I grabbed just that one envelope
from the pile and opened it.

01:35:39.420 --> 01:35:41.260
In it were five applications

01:35:41.260 --> 01:35:45.540
for something called the Scholastic
Children's Defense Fund Fellowship.

01:35:45.540 --> 01:35:49.520
I was immediately intrigued
because, like many kids,

01:35:49.520 --> 01:35:52.100
I had grown up reading
Scholastic books,

01:35:52.100 --> 01:35:56.820
and I had especially been obsessed
with Scholastic Book Club flyers.

01:35:56.820 --> 01:36:00.570
I read an application and
I saw that I could apply

01:36:00.570 --> 01:36:03.500
to be a summer fellow
assigned to one of a variety

01:36:03.500 --> 01:36:08.010 position:56%
of departments, including editorial.

01:36:08.010 --> 01:36:12.660
Editorial, something stirred
in my spirit and I started

01:36:12.660 --> 01:36:16.150
to get really excited because
I knew that this was it.

01:36:16.150 --> 01:36:20.240
This was the meaningful
summer job that I would do.

01:36:20.240 --> 01:36:22.900
Being an editor had never once
crossed my mind, but sure,

01:36:22.900 --> 01:36:26.070
I had often been happy to
tell my friends what was wrong

01:36:26.070 --> 01:36:29.100
with their book reports
and term papers.

01:36:29.100 --> 01:36:31.220
I love to read books,
and think about books,

01:36:31.220 --> 01:36:34.170
the write about books,
and talk about books.

01:36:34.170 --> 01:36:35.710
So why not?

01:36:35.710 --> 01:36:38.200
The applications at the
fellowship would take place

01:36:38.200 --> 01:36:40.890
at Scholastic's headquarters
in New York City

01:36:40.890 --> 01:36:42.350
