01:41:40.240 --> 01:41:43.160
I am now senior editor for
those same two imprints.

01:41:43.160 --> 01:41:45.740
I have a particular
passion for comics

01:41:45.740 --> 01:41:48.660
and acquiring graphic
novels for every reader.

01:41:48.660 --> 01:41:51.670
I've edited a number of New York
Times and USA Today bestsellers,

01:41:51.670 --> 01:41:54.660
as well as Eisner Award winners.

01:41:54.660 --> 01:41:57.150
I have the pleasure of working with
some of the most talented writers

01:41:57.150 --> 01:42:00.600 position:56%
and cartoonists around, such as
Reyna Talgameyer [assumed spelling],

01:42:00.600 --> 01:42:06.180
Kazu Kibuishi, Mike Maihack,
Jeff Smith, and Kate Messner.

01:42:06.180 --> 01:42:09.740
Professionally these past 10
years have been incredible.

01:42:09.740 --> 01:42:13.200
I would like to say that one major,
essential theme of my career,

01:42:13.200 --> 01:42:17.400
which I talk about any chance
I get, has been mentorship.

01:42:17.400 --> 01:42:20.530
I've had several brilliant
mentors over the years,

01:42:20.530 --> 01:42:23.480
and my growth through those
relationships has been at the core

01:42:23.480 --> 01:42:26.420
of my personal and
professional development.

01:42:26.420 --> 01:42:28.900
But one thing I recently
learned is that it's important

01:42:28.900 --> 01:42:33.080
to identify both mentors
and sponsors.

01:42:33.080 --> 01:42:35.820
Mentors usually operate
as sounding boards

01:42:35.820 --> 01:42:38.640
and offer guidance
on an informal level.

01:42:38.640 --> 01:42:41.940
Conversations might be more
personal and anecdotal.

01:42:41.940 --> 01:42:46.320
Sponsors take more of a directly
professional investment in you

01:42:46.320 --> 01:42:49.550
and use their influence to
market you to someone else,

01:42:49.550 --> 01:42:53.250
thereby creating or furthering
an opportunity for you to move

01:42:53.250 --> 01:42:55.710
to the next level in your career.

01:42:55.710 --> 01:42:58.170
I mention this because this is
something I wish I had learned

01:42:58.170 --> 01:42:59.880
early on.

