in on their class just because
there's always something I can learn

02:37:31.580 --> 02:37:33.410
about the process of writing.

02:37:33.410 --> 02:37:38.050
When I was a kid I was really
afraid of poetry, so I --

02:37:38.050 --> 02:37:41.760
as an adult I had to kind of
work through that and really read

02:37:41.760 --> 02:37:47.710
and reread poetry and study poets
and find the poets who I understood

02:37:47.710 --> 02:37:50.780
and just crack that code of poetry

02:37:50.780 --> 02:37:54.070
because I didn't want
that fear to silence me.

02:37:54.070 --> 02:37:57.060
And I think so often it is
our fears that silence us

02:37:57.060 --> 02:37:58.360
and keep us from writing.

02:37:58.360 --> 02:38:05.260 position:56%
And I think it's asking ourselves
the question, what do we want to say

02:38:05.260 --> 02:38:07.580
and what do we want to
change and how do we want

02:38:07.580 --> 02:38:09.610
to change it through our words?

02:38:09.610 --> 02:38:13.770
And so with writing for children,
you know, it's that slippery slope.

02:38:13.770 --> 02:38:15.800
You can't be didactic.

02:38:15.800 --> 02:38:17.200
You -- I would say I write --

02:38:17.200 --> 02:38:19.600
I don't write to teach,
I write to learn.

02:38:19.600 --> 02:38:21.580
If I wanted to teach
I'd write textbooks.

02:38:21.580 --> 02:38:23.750
So I think sometimes people go
and think I'm going to write

02:38:23.750 --> 02:38:26.520
for young people because
I want to teach them this

02:38:26.520 --> 02:38:27.980
or I want to show them that.

02:38:27.980 --> 02:38:30.860
And kids read for the
same reason we read,

02:38:30.860 --> 02:38:32.690
they read to hear a great story.

02:38:32.690 --> 02:38:35.300
And through that great
story they learn empathy.

02:38:35.300 --> 02:38:38.540
They learn understanding,
and they learn how

02:38:38.540 --> 02:38:40.430
to -- they become empowered.

02:38:40.430 --> 02:38:42.730
But the first step of
that writing is getting

02:38:42.730 --> 02:38:44.940
that good story on the page.

02:38:44.940 --> 02:38:49.280
And then after taking -- I
took those writing classes

02:38:49.280 --> 02:38:52.080
and I finally found a publisher
at Bantam Doubleday Dell,

02:38:52.080 --> 02:38:55.340
which is now Random House,
and worked with Wendy Lamb,

02:38:55.340 --> 02:38:57.340
who was queen of the slush pile.

02:38:57.340 --> 02:39:00.420
She's the one who found
Christopher Paul Curtis and lots

02:39:00.420 --> 02:39:04.750
of other great writers and
then eventually came to work --

02:39:04.750 --> 02:39:10.440
came to write at Penguin where I've
been working with the same editor

02:39:10.440 --> 02:39:13.600
for 14 years now, which
is kind of crazy.

02:39:13.600 --> 02:39:18.980
But -- and who lets me write
basically what I want to write,

02:39:18.980 --> 02:39:23.830
but I write what I
care deeply about,

02:39:23.830 --> 02:39:25.940
and I care deeply about
young people.

02:39:25.940 --> 02:39:30.880
As WNDB talks about seeing images
of themselves in the world,

02:39:30.880 --> 02:39:34.820
because for me as a child
those images were absent.

02:39:34.820 --> 02:39:38.500
You had to look long and hard
to find reflections of yourself.

02:39:38.500 --> 02:39:41.720
Not only reflections of yourself,
but reflections of yourself

02:39:41.720 --> 02:39:44.660
that were written by
people who look like you.

02:39:44.660 --> 02:39:48.730
There were lots of books that
were written by white folks

02:39:48.730 --> 02:39:50.990
about black people, but
there -- I couldn't --

02:39:50.990 --> 02:39:53.600
I had a hard time finding
books where the --

02:39:53.600 --> 02:39:59.800
where I could trace the book to
an African American female author.

02:39:59.800 --> 02:40:01.630
So it was really important to me.

02:40:01.630 --> 02:40:03.920
And it was a journey.

02:40:03.920 --> 02:40:08.570
So I am going to read a short
section from my adult book,

02:40:08.570 --> 02:40:11.030
and I'm not leaving the
world of children's books

02:40:11.030 --> 02:40:13.780
for good, I'm coming back.

02:40:13.780 --> 02:40:20.570
But I was thinking in terms of what
our stories are and the importance

02:40:20.570 --> 02:40:23.090
of putting those stories
on the page.

02:40:23.090 --> 02:40:25.340
This book is a biography

02:40:25.340 --> 02:40:29.260
of the neighborhood I grew
up, which is Bushwick.

02:40:29.260 --> 02:40:33.500
So Bushwick -- so all the
Bushwick stuff is true,

02:40:33.500 --> 02:40:38.000
and then fictive element of
it are the four young women

02:40:38.000 --> 02:40:41.600
who are walking through
this real place.

02:40:41.600 --> 02:40:47.640
And I think with writing you're
constantly breaking the rules.

02:40:47.640 --> 02:40:53.120
So I think it's so important to
read across genre, to read poetry

02:40:53.120 --> 02:40:56.290
and fiction, to read
children's books and adult books,

02:40:56.290 --> 02:40:58.820
because you create --
each time a writer sits

02:40:58.820 --> 02:41:03.120 position:56%
down to create a book you're telling
a new story and you're telling it

02:41:03.120 --> 02:41:06.790
in a way that only you
can tell that story.

02:41:06.790 --> 02:41:10.920
So, unfortunately, with publishers
sometimes they can be lazy

02:41:10.920 --> 02:41:13.540
so they want to see
how that book is going

02:41:13.540 --> 02:41:15.010
to have an impact on the world.

02:41:15.010 --> 02:41:18.720
So you can't say, well, remember
[inaudible] Between the World

02:41:18.720 --> 02:41:24.270
and Me, or remember Claude McKay's
Manchild in the Promised Land

02:41:24.270 --> 02:41:26.970
or Alice Walker's Color Purple.

02:41:26.970 --> 02:41:29.220
And then they go, oh yes, so
you're writing a vignette.

02:41:29.220 --> 02:41:31.210
Oh yes, so you're writing
about that experience.

02:41:31.210 --> 02:41:34.730
So you have to have some kind
of mirror, but you also have

02:41:34.730 --> 02:41:38.020
to have this original,
original story.

02:41:39.430 --> 02:41:41.730
So --

02:41:50.350 --> 02:41:55.350
Sorry. This is Kwame's copy of the
book that I promised to bring him,

02:41:55.350 --> 02:41:57.320
so I didn't want to dog ear it

02:41:57.320 --> 02:41:59.680
because then he would think
I was giving him some used

02:41:59.680 --> 02:42:00.980
stuff [laughter].

