02:42:02.800 --> 02:42:04.600
You have yours.

02:42:04.600 --> 02:42:08.770
Oh man, sorry, this is Jason's
copy of my book but [laughter].

02:42:13.710 --> 02:42:16.940
I imagine the women my father
brought home, taking a place

02:42:16.940 --> 02:42:18.880
until my mother returned.

02:42:18.880 --> 02:42:22.010
Each shh, my kids are sleeping.

02:42:22.010 --> 02:42:27.000 position:56%
Each, oh Lord, look at your
precious babies, brought her closer.

02:42:27.000 --> 02:42:29.860
I lay in bed and listened as
the clink of ice in glasses

02:42:29.860 --> 02:42:33.390
and the hush laughter gave
way to size and moans.

02:42:33.390 --> 02:42:36.590
I imagined waking up with a
new woman, her hair in curlers,

02:42:36.590 --> 02:42:40.410
holding her robe closed with one
hand, asking if I wanted pancakes

02:42:40.410 --> 02:42:45.050 position:56%
or cereal, scouring the cabinets for
the last of the Aunt Jemima syrup,

02:42:45.050 --> 02:42:49.190
sprinkling a bit of cinnamon
and sugar when there was none.

02:42:49.190 --> 02:42:53.610 position:56%
I imagined strong, sure hands
pulling my hair into tight cornrows,

02:42:53.610 --> 02:42:56.910 position:56%
telling my brother to take his thumb
out of his mouth, kissing my father

02:42:56.910 --> 02:42:59.750
on the lips as he headed
off to work.

02:42:59.750 --> 02:43:02.640
I imagined the four of us at the
kitchen table, the thick stink

02:43:02.640 --> 02:43:07.060
of boiling chitins gone, replaced
by hot sauce and white rice

02:43:07.060 --> 02:43:10.520
and the woman who came to stay
until my mother returned asking

02:43:10.520 --> 02:43:12.990
if I wanted a little or a lot.

02:43:12.990 --> 02:43:15.830
Years later I would tell this to
Sister Sonja [assumed spelling],

02:43:15.830 --> 02:43:19.570
wanting her to know that I had
dreamed our family whole again,

02:43:19.570 --> 02:43:23.330
that I had believed
wholeness was on its way.

02:43:23.330 --> 02:43:27.170 position:56%
In a jar on the counter of Poncho
Store there were pickled pigs' feet,

02:43:27.170 --> 02:43:30.640
and he'd scoop up -- that he
would scoop out into brown paper.

02:43:30.640 --> 02:43:32.170
When you said I want
to choose my own,

02:43:32.170 --> 02:43:34.470
Poncho said no choosing, I choose.

02:43:34.470 --> 02:43:37.260
His old man eyes moving
over your body,

02:43:37.260 --> 02:43:40.860
and if you were hungry
enough you let him.

02:43:40.860 --> 02:43:44.220
I imagined the four of us,
brother, father, new woman, me,

02:43:44.220 --> 02:43:47.810
sucking the last of the pickled
meat from the pig's foot bone,

02:43:47.810 --> 02:43:51.070
wrapping the cartilage and
bone back into the brown paper,

02:43:51.070 --> 02:43:53.610
washing it down with Dr. Pepper.

02:43:53.610 --> 02:43:57.000
Pork rinds were packaged
and sold for 15 cents

02:43:57.000 --> 02:43:59.720
with hot sauce sprinkled
into a plastic bag.

02:43:59.720 --> 02:44:01.510
You almost had a meal.

02:44:01.510 --> 02:44:06.250
My brother ate his without the
sauce, sometimes adding more salt.

02:44:06.250 --> 02:44:09.200 position:56%
On good days our father took us
around the corner and let us buy ham

02:44:09.200 --> 02:44:12.800
and cheese heroes, the boiled ham
cut into thin slices and layered

02:44:12.800 --> 02:44:16.070
over Italian bread already
spread thick with Mayo.

02:44:16.070 --> 02:44:19.520
Some days my brother preferred
the square cuts of spiced ham

02:44:19.520 --> 02:44:24.450
with its tiny speckles of
white fat, that was before.

02:44:24.450 --> 02:44:28.040
The woman who came didn't tiptoe
through our house in the night,

02:44:28.040 --> 02:44:31.950
didn't ask for just a taste
when my offered her whiskey,

02:44:31.950 --> 02:44:35.400
didn't sit with us eating
pig's feet and spiced ham.

02:44:35.400 --> 02:44:38.470
She came by way of the Nation
of Islam, her head wrapped,

02:44:38.470 --> 02:44:41.860
her dark dress draping
down below her ankles.

02:44:41.860 --> 02:44:44.650
She said my name is Sister
Loretta, her Bible --

02:44:44.650 --> 02:44:48.310
her body a temple covered and
far away from my father's.

02:44:48.310 --> 02:44:51.410
Her thin face free of
swine filled makeup

02:44:51.410 --> 02:44:54.720
with which unenlightened
women painted their faces.

02:44:54.720 --> 02:44:57.860
She said, I know how
amazing and lovely I am.

02:44:57.860 --> 02:45:01.090
When she looked down at us
and smiled her dark face broke

02:45:01.090 --> 02:45:05.540
into something open and
hungry and beautiful.

02:45:05.540 --> 02:45:07.900
She said your father is
ready to change his life.

02:45:07.900 --> 02:45:10.370
She said, the food you're
eating is the white devil's plan

02:45:10.370 --> 02:45:12.150
to kill our people.

02:45:12.150 --> 02:45:14.950
She came into our apartment
on a Sunday morning pulling

02:45:14.950 --> 02:45:19.670 position:56%
down dusty pots and pans from the
cabinet to wash in warm soapy water,

02:45:19.670 --> 02:45:21.320
humming slowly as she worked.

02:45:21.320 --> 02:45:24.450
My father at the table
reading from the Koran,

02:45:24.450 --> 02:45:28.710
a watery Brooklyn sunlight
falling over the pages.

02:45:28.710 --> 02:45:30.510
Her hands were large and moved

02:45:30.510 --> 02:45:33.060
as thought they had always
known our tiny kitchen,

02:45:33.060 --> 02:45:36.900
with its yellowing sink and
peeling linoleum counter.

02:45:36.900 --> 02:45:41.110 position:56%
I watched them, imagining they were
my mothers, and that they were again

02:45:41.110 --> 02:45:43.330
in Sweet Grove with our broken --

02:45:43.330 --> 02:45:45.430
and that we were again
in Sweet Grove

02:45:45.430 --> 02:45:48.200
with our broken stove
and dusty bookshelves.

02:45:48.200 --> 02:45:50.930
I sat in the kitchen
doorway, my knees pulled

02:45:50.930 --> 02:45:54.300
up to my chin, eyes
lifted toward her.

02:45:54.300 --> 02:45:56.580
Her breasts were heavy
beneath the dark dress,

02:45:56.580 --> 02:45:58.190
but she wasn't a heavy woman.

02:45:58.190 --> 02:46:02.050
Still, her body seemed to hold
promises of curves, of the soft

02:46:02.050 --> 02:46:05.720
and deep spaces I was just
beginning to understand.

02:46:05.720 --> 02:46:09.480
One day I'd have full
breast, hips, and large hands.

02:46:09.480 --> 02:46:15.150
One day my body would tell the
world stories beneath the fabric

02:46:15.150 --> 02:46:17.960
of my clothes.

02:46:17.960 --> 02:46:23.600
So one thing, when I was writing
Another Brooklyn I realized

02:46:23.600 --> 02:46:28.330
that so many of the
stories on the page --

02:46:28.330 --> 02:46:33.530
in the world are not always
representative of the kind

02:46:33.530 --> 02:46:36.060
of intricacies of our growing up.

02:46:36.060 --> 02:46:40.350
I always say, you know, especially
in families of color, you know,

02:46:40.350 --> 02:46:42.630
you throw a stone and you
hit the uncle in prison.

02:46:42.630 --> 02:46:45.110
You throw another stone and
you hit the poor relatives.

02:46:45.110 --> 02:46:48.110
Or they throw a stone and hit
you, their poor relatives.

02:46:48.110 --> 02:46:52.690
But there are all these nuances to
our community, all these stories

02:46:52.690 --> 02:46:56.870
that have not been told because
of this layer of shame to them.

02:46:56.870 --> 02:47:02.570
And I think that if we tell
those stories with the level

02:47:02.570 --> 02:47:06.320 position:56%
of deep respect that we have, I'm
thinking of When I Was the Greatest,

02:47:06.320 --> 02:47:09.160
Jason's book, and the first time
reading that and thinking, wow,

02:47:09.160 --> 02:47:10.570
he's nailing all of this.

02:47:10.570 --> 02:47:11.870
He's telling the truth.

02:47:11.870 --> 02:47:16.340
And for fiction that's the first
point that we need to bring

02:47:16.340 --> 02:47:19.440
to the page, is that
deep and important truth

02:47:19.440 --> 02:47:21.480
and then the rest follows.

02:47:21.480 --> 02:47:24.780
So I'm happy to be here
in the room with you all.

02:47:24.780 --> 02:47:26.930
And now Kwame is coming up
and I'm going to sit down

02:47:26.930 --> 02:47:29.060
and we're going to
talk junk [laughter].

