03:06:51.180 --> 03:06:54.510
And so, yeah, so Ruth
Foreman you all.

03:06:54.510 --> 03:07:01.290
[ Applause ]

03:07:01.290 --> 03:07:02.590
&gt;&gt; Jacqueline Woodson:
The first book I wrote

03:07:02.590 --> 03:07:04.470
in verse was a book
called Locomotion.

03:07:04.470 --> 03:07:07.460
And it was a collection of poems
told from the point of view

03:07:07.460 --> 03:07:10.980
of an 11 year old boy
who was in foster care

03:07:10.980 --> 03:07:12.720
and separated from his sister.

03:07:12.720 --> 03:07:18.430
And he's in the fifth grade and
his teacher introduces poetry

03:07:18.430 --> 03:07:21.730
and different forms and he realizes

03:07:21.730 --> 03:07:26.790
that he can tell his
story through this form.

03:07:26.790 --> 03:07:30.320
So -- and that -- this
is where his genius lies.

03:07:30.320 --> 03:07:35.270
And so I didn't know that I was
going to write a book in verse,

03:07:35.270 --> 03:07:39.320
but as I wrote and rewrote I
realized that I would be breaking

03:07:39.320 --> 03:07:43.510 position:56%
that first rule of writing, which is
show don't tell, if I had this story

03:07:43.510 --> 03:07:47.900 position:56%
of this boy writing poetry and the
whole book wasn't representing that.

03:07:47.900 --> 03:07:52.820
And so that -- at that point
I was reading a ton of poetry

03:07:52.820 --> 03:07:56.220
and researching different form --
you know, studying different forms.

03:07:56.220 --> 03:07:58.700
So when I got the Brown
Girl Dreaming,

03:07:58.700 --> 03:08:02.930
again I knew I was writing a memoir
and I was writing down memory,

03:08:02.930 --> 03:08:06.190
and I know that memory came in
these small moments with all

03:08:06.190 --> 03:08:07.880
of this white space around it.

03:08:07.880 --> 03:08:10.590
So the form was decided that way.

03:08:10.590 --> 03:08:11.890
It made sense.

03:08:11.890 --> 03:08:14.000
And then as I went back --

03:08:14.000 --> 03:08:18.190
as I started rewriting I realized
I wanted to begin to shape it

03:08:18.190 --> 03:08:23.640
so that the poetry
was more intentional.

03:08:23.640 --> 03:08:29.000
And then I added the haiku, so it's
interspersed with all these how

03:08:29.000 --> 03:08:34.530
to listen haiku, and those were
to basically be this kind of pull

03:08:34.530 --> 03:08:36.770
out on how one becomes a writer.

03:08:36.770 --> 03:08:40.770
So the writing and the rewriting
helped decide what the eventual

03:08:40.770 --> 03:08:42.130
form was.

03:08:42.130 --> 03:08:45.450
&gt;&gt; Kwame Alexander: I think
for me it -- and this is --

03:08:45.450 --> 03:08:47.820
we can sort of bring this
back full circle because we're

03:08:47.820 --> 03:08:53.470
about to close out, and this
is a black arts movement event,

03:08:53.470 --> 03:08:55.280
tribute, celebration.

03:08:55.280 --> 03:08:59.850
For me, when I look back at the
poets that I read and studied

03:08:59.850 --> 03:09:04.190
when I -- and got excited about
in college and beyond, it was --

03:09:04.190 --> 03:09:10.060
it was Haki Madhubudi's But
He Was Cool, but him was cool,

03:09:10.060 --> 03:09:12.030
him was refrigerator cool.

03:09:12.030 --> 03:09:13.330
And it was sort of taking these --

03:09:13.330 --> 03:09:17.590
and Nikki Giovanni's I Was Born in
the Congo, which is a real cool,

03:09:17.590 --> 03:09:19.740
hip way to say once upon a time.

03:09:19.740 --> 03:09:22.620
I mean, but it really --
you know, and so these poets

03:09:22.620 --> 03:09:26.620
from the black arts movement were
writing these stories in one poem.

03:09:26.620 --> 03:09:28.920
They were giving you
a beginning, a middle,

03:09:28.920 --> 03:09:31.660
and an end in 20 and
30 and 40 lines.

03:09:31.660 --> 03:09:34.470
And, of course, that came
from the Harlem renaissance,

03:09:34.470 --> 03:09:36.080
Lakes and Hughes.

03:09:36.080 --> 03:09:39.250
I woke up this morning
about half past three.

03:09:39.250 --> 03:09:41.690
All the ladies in town
were gathered around me.

03:09:41.690 --> 03:09:43.090
Sweet gals was a moaning.

03:09:43.090 --> 03:09:44.390
Sylvester is going to die.

03:09:44.390 --> 03:09:46.460
And a hundred pretty ladies
bowed their heads to cry.

03:09:46.460 --> 03:09:49.060
I woke up a little later,
about half passed four.

03:09:49.060 --> 03:09:51.600
The doctors and undertakers
both at my door.

03:09:51.600 --> 03:09:53.520 position:56%
Tell all my mourners to mourn in red

03:09:53.520 --> 03:09:55.970
because there ain't no
sense in me being dead.

03:09:55.970 --> 03:09:57.270
He's telling a story.

03:09:57.270 --> 03:09:58.570 position:56%
And so you're getting these stories.

03:09:58.570 --> 03:10:01.210
And so when I started writing
poetry I was telling stories

03:10:01.210 --> 03:10:02.510
in these poems.

03:10:02.510 --> 03:10:05.500
And so it was -- it took
me maybe about 15 years,

03:10:05.500 --> 03:10:07.320
but I feel like it was a
natural progression to get

03:10:07.320 --> 03:10:10.780
to the point where, okay,
well, I sort of figured out how

03:10:10.780 --> 03:10:13.750
to have fun telling
stories and poems,

03:10:13.750 --> 03:10:18.230
how can I now group these poems
together and tell a story novel

03:10:18.230 --> 03:10:20.060
in a full, complete novel.

03:10:20.060 --> 03:10:22.510
And the first book that I read
that sort of showed me that that

03:10:22.510 --> 03:10:24.180
that was possible was two books.

03:10:24.180 --> 03:10:26.610 position:56%
It was Sharon Creech's Love That Dog

03:10:26.610 --> 03:10:31.810
and it was Hope Anita Smith's
Keeping the Night Watch

03:10:31.810 --> 03:10:33.630
and The Way a Door Closes.

03:10:33.630 --> 03:10:38.520
And those are really
phenomenal novellas in verse.

